You are correct in your understanding of Svelte's reactivity. If a function is used in a `{#if}` block as a condition, and the function's output depends on reactive variables, the `{#if}` block itself may not update reactively as the function is not re-invoked automatically when its dependencies change. Svelte's reactivity is based on assignments to reactive variables, not on the result of function calls.

To address this, you can assign the result of the function to a reactive variable, as you suggested. By doing this, whenever the underlying reactive dependencies change, the variable will be updated, and Svelte will reactively update the `{#if}` block in the DOM. For example:

```svelte
$: reactiveCondition = myFunction();

{#if reactiveCondition}
    <!-- Your conditional content -->
{/if}
```

In this example, `reactiveCondition` will be updated whenever any reactive variable inside `myFunction()` changes, ensuring the `{#if}` block reacts to those changes.

