In JavaScript, you can destructure objects to extract their properties as individual variables, which can be useful for finer-grained reactivity in frameworks like Svelte. The syntax for object destructuring is:

```javascript
const myObject = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 };
const { a, b, c } = myObject;
```

This creates three new variables `a`, `b`, and `c`, each holding the corresponding values from `myObject`. This way, you can work with these values as primitives, which can be more efficient in reactive contexts, as changes to one property won't trigger updates related to other properties. However, remember that destructuring creates a shallow copy, so changes to nested objects or arrays will still affect the original object.

