In JSDoc, to annotate a function parameter that is an object with properties from another type (like `Todo` in your case), you can use the `Partial<T>` type or simply define the type of each property directly. `Partial<T>` is a TypeScript utility type which makes all properties of `T` optional. While JSDoc doesn't natively support TypeScript's utility types, you can simulate this behavior by specifying each property as optional.

In your case, `updatedTodo` seems to be an object that may have any of the properties of a `Todo` but not necessarily all of them. Here's how you can annotate it in JSDoc:

```javascript
/**
 * Update todo properties
 * @param {{ id?: number, name?: string, completed?: boolean }} updatedTodo
 */
function update(updatedTodo) {
  // ...
}
```

Here, each property of the `Todo` interface is marked as optional using `?`. This means `updatedTodo` can have any combination of these properties, including all, some, or none of them.

Alternatively, if you have a TypeScript environment, you could directly use `Partial<Todo>`:

```typescript
/**
 * Update todo properties
 * @param {Partial<import('./types').Todo>} updatedTodo
 */
function update(updatedTodo) {
  // ...
}
```

However, this approach is more suitable if your JSDoc comments are being processed in a TypeScript-aware toolchain.

