It seems there was an issue with the way the CSV string was split into rows and fields, which resulted in an incorrect conversion. Let's refine the function to properly handle CSV strings and convert them into an array of objects:

1. We'll first split the CSV string into rows.
2. Extract headers from the first row.
3. Process each subsequent row, splitting it into fields.
4. For each field, we'll remove any escaping of double quotes and trim extra quotes.
5. Combine the fields with the headers to create a dictionary for each row.
6. Add each dictionary to an array representing the data.

Here's the corrected function implementation:

```javascript
function csvToArray(csvString) {
  // Split the CSV string into rows
  const rows = csvString.trim().split("\n");

  // Extract headers from the first row
  const headers = rows[0].split(",");

  // Initialize an array to hold the parsed data
  const data = [];

  // Process each row except the header
  for (let i = 1; i < rows.length; i++) {
    // Split the row into fields
    const fields = rows[i].split(",");

    // Create a dictionary for the row
    const rowData = {};
    for (let j = 0; j < headers.length; j++) {
      // Remove any double quote escaping and trim extra quotes
      const field = fields[j].replace('""', '"').trim('"');

      // Add the field to the row dictionary
      rowData[headers[j]] = field;
    }

    // Add the row dictionary to the data array
    data.push(rowData);
  }

  return data;
}

// Example usage with a CSV string
const csvString = `
id,Name,Producer,Vintage,Purchased,Consumed
1,Wine A,Producer A,2020,2021-01-01,2021-12-31
2,Wine B,Producer B,2019,2020-05-10,2021-05-10
`;

// Convert the CSV string to an array of objects
const arrayData = csvToArray(csvString);
console.log(arrayData);
```

This function will convert your CSV string into an array of objects, each object representing a row of the CSV, with keys corresponding to the headers and values to the respective fields.

